SKs have been given the cold shoulder for a long time when it comes to &quot;useful&quot; pre-combat spells for the group...<br>
<br>
note, once you start playing a SK, due to not having many useful buffs, you kinda forget you CAN pre-combat buff something useful finally!<br>
<br>
The spell is annoying to load, but I usually plop it on the MT whether they want it or not....  I usually kid in gsay &quot;warrior_01 is now scary&quot;...<br>
<br>
all of a sudden mr warrior has a lot larger margin for error.<br>
Voice line has a noticeable effect on the non-uber... and adds a nice margin of error for even the well equipped.<br>
<br>
most of the time, the warrior says nothing... and I am just as happy if we just keel stuff...  but every so often it is nice to hear &quot;got that aggro buff?&quot; from a warrior.<br>
<br>
If I can't tank it... then I'll do my best to make sure someone else can... Its the same thing I have been doin for three years, but voice makes it easier.<br>
<br>
Now if I can train a few less uber warriors how taunt works and why the SK uber aggroing and then the warrior TAUNTing is a good thing. (hail an ignored chanter_01)  Voice isnt the only way SK can give warriors aggro.<br>
<br>
You met some disgruntled SK... insist on voice...  ask in gsay and REMIND him in gsay.  The point ya want to get across is the value to the GROUP of voice.  Aggro is ALWAYS a team goal... voice makes the team's job easier.<br>
<br>
P.S. <br>
Please cut my less experienced SK brethren some slack... for the first time since release, SK actually have to make a choice for their spell slots...  they are quite valuable now, where before the SK always had the same spells memmed more often than not. Voice now has a large cost that most Warriors might not ever understand.<br>
Emphasize the value to the group and most SK will see the light.  Being useful to a group directly through buffs is a little weird for some Shadowknights.  They will come around.<br>
<br>
Baazghul &quot;Brik&quot; Bludgaard <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=graalthedorf>Graal the Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 130<br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/23/02 12:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2497.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Voice</span><hr size=1> There was on thing that Brik brought up that I think isn't well understood by warriors.<br>
<br>
I'm a paladin...I don't have buffs that will give a warrior aggro. Even so, I can essentially give them all the aggro they need for a fight. If I stun the mob twice as its coming in and during initial engagement, I gain a ton of aggro. Any successful taunt by the warrior gives him my aggro+1. He now has solid aggro for the rest of the fight. A caster has to be a complete bonehead to steal aggro from the warrior after that.<br>
<br>
Very few warriors I have grouped with understand that concept. Whenever I stun at initial engagement, or when the mob turns to the slower, etc. they think I am showboating or trying to steal aggro from them. <br>
<br>
Would be nice if more warriors understood how to take advantage of high aggro hybrids+taunt. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
